"this year Greta Gerwig solo feature directorial debut Ladybird stars Saoirse Ronan as Christine, who now goes by the name Ladybird"
"She is finishing up high school at a Catholic school in Sacramento and she is really eager to get out of town and into college all the way on the East Coast, far far away from home"
"The movie isn't based on girl wigs life, but she has said that the movie does contain certain ideas that have truth to her and you can really feel it while you're watching the movie"
It works especially well with the way that Lady Bird looks at Sacramento
"I personally didn't experience exactly this when choosing where to go to college, but I do very much understand and connect to the thought that something special is out there and it's somewhere that you're not and that intense pulling you might have towards it"
"I did have that feeling a little while moving to La, and girl work really captures that idea and feeling so beautifully in a way that both well represents Ladybirds current disdain for her hometown, but also while conveying what makes it a special place, and that's a balance that's really important throughout the entire film"
"And then, of course there's Saoirse Ronan performance and she is just something else from Hanna to Brooklyn to this, and so much more, her range is incredible and so is her ability to wholly become a character"
"By the end of this, Lady Bird truly felt like a person I knew and I enjoyed getting to know, and that speaks to both how well-rounded the character is and also how well Gerwig establishes the highs and lows of growing up"
